f=Cybersecurity/keyring/marketplace/secrets-governance/SKILL.md · in=Securely manage your application secrets database credentials, API keys, tokens, certificates, sensitive configuration using industry-standard tools practices. skill covers full lifecycle secrets management: secure storage, access control, rotation, auditing. · p=Secrets keys your infrastructure. Hardcoded credentials, unrotated keys, secrets stored configuration files environment variables among common dangerous security vulnerabilities. Proper secrets management ensures credentials stored securely, accessed authorized services, rotated regularly, audited compliance. · wu=Setting new secrets management infrastructure., Rotating database credentials, API keys, certificates., Auditing current secrets storage practices., Responding potential credential leak., Implementing secrets management CI/CD pipelines., Managing secrets across multiple environments (dev/staging/prod). · h3:HashiCorp Vault=HashiCorp Vault comprehensive secrets management solution. provides: · h3:HashiCorp Vault=**Dynamic Secrets**: Generate on-demand, short-lived credentials databases, cloud providers, more., **Encryption Service**: Encrypt/decrypt data without managing encryption keys., **Key Rotation**: Automatic rotation secrets., **Audit Logging**: Comprehensive audit trail secret access. · h3:HashiCorp Vault=`# Start Vault in development mode (never for production) \· vault server -dev \·  \· # Set the VAULT_ADDR environment variable \· export VAULT_ADDR='http://127.0.0.1:8200'` · h3:HashiCorp Vault=`storage "raft" { \· path = "/vault/data" \· node_id = "node1" \· } \· ` · h3:HashiCorp Vault=**Basic Vault Setup:** **Production Vault Configuration (Raft Storage):** · h3:AWS Secrets Manager=`# Create a secret \· aws secretsmanager create-secret \ \· --name prod/mysql/db1 \ \· --secret-string '{"username":"dbadmin","password":"InitialPassword123!"}' \· ` · h3:AWS Secrets Manager=`import json \· import boto3 \· import logging \·  \· logger = logging.getLogger()` · h3:AWS Secrets Manager=AWS-native secrets management automatic rotation RDS databases. **Creating Rotating Secret:** **Automatic Rotation Lambda:** · h3:Azure Key Vault=`# Create a Key Vault \· az keyvault create \ \· --name myvault \ \· --resource-group myrg \ \· --location eastus` · h3:Azure Key Vault=Microsoft's cloud-based secrets management HSM-backed key protection. · h3:Google Secret Manager=`# Create a secret \· echo -n "my-secret-password" \| gcloud secrets create my-secret \ \· --data-file=- \·  \· # Access a secret` · h3:Google Secret Manager=GCP-native secrets management IAM integration. · h3:Kubernetes Secrets=`apiVersion: v1 \· kind: Secret \· metadata: \· name: app-secrets \· type: Opaque` · h3:Kubernetes Secrets=Kubernetes-native secret storage (base64 encoded, consider using external secrets operators production). **Best Practice:** Use external secrets operators (e.g., External Secrets Operator, Sealed Secrets) sync secrets Vault cloud providers Kubernetes rather storing them cluster directly. · h3:Secret Creation=Use strong, randomly generated passwords (min characters), Use separate secrets environment service, Implement least-privilege access secrets, ✅ Enable secret versioning, Never hardcode secrets code, Never commit secrets version control, Never share secrets messaging apps email, Never log secrets include them error messages · h3:Secret Rotation=Rotate database credentials days, Rotate API keys 180 days employee departure, Automate rotation possible, Test rotation procedures regularly, Never share secret across multiple services, Never extend rotation periods without justification · h3:Access Control=Implement least-privilege access secrets, Use role-based access control (RBAC) secret management, Enable audit logging secret access, Use short-lived credentials possible, Never use root/admin accounts routine secret access, Never bypass access controls convenience · h3:Monitoring and Auditing=Monitor unauthorized secret access attempts, Alert unusual secret access patterns, Regularly audit secret usage access, Keep audit logs minimum year, Review revoke unused secrets · h2:Manual Rotation Process=automated rotation available: **Generate new credentials** secrets manager **Update dependent services** new credentials **Test new credentials** thoroughly **Deprecate old credentials** (mark deprecated, allow grace period) **Revoke old credentials** after confirmation services use new ones **Document rotation** including date, reason, any issues encountered · of=`## Secrets Management Review \· Tool: [Vault / AWS SM / Azure KV / GCP SM / K8s] \· Secrets managed: [count] \· Last rotation: [date] \· Rotation cadence: [frequency] \· Access control: [RBAC configured? \· audit logging enabled?]` · pr=**Never hardcode secrets** secrets code compromised secrets. **Rotate regularly** rotation routine, fire drill. **Least privilege** secret grants minimum access needed. **Audit everything** access, change, rotation logged. **Test rotations** untested rotation procedures fail needed most. **Short-lived over static** dynamic, time-limited secrets better long-lived static ones. **Seperate environment** dev secrets never touch production. · f=**No secrets manager available** use encrypted environment variables manual rotation, labeled "provisional." Immediately flag risk warden., **Legacy hardcoded secrets found** document location, scope, risk. Prioritize migration secrets manager. secret treated compromised until confirmed otherwise., **Rotation failure** revert previous credentials immediately, document failure, reschedule rotation after fixing issue. · b:with Other Skills=**access-control-policy** (Hack23): secrets access follows RBAC least-privilege model., **keyring's privileged-access-management** (sibling): service account machine identity secrets follow PAM discipline., **aegis/ops (Engineering)**: enforce no-secrets-in-code code review; skill provides vaulting alternative they reference., **cortex (Cybersecurity)**: leaked secret detection event; found secrets alert cortex IR., **warden**: secrets gaps (no vault, unrotated keys, hardcoded creds) register risks.